t to its own ideals: to democracy and the Enlightenment trinity of liberty, equality, and fraternity. In the most fundamental sense, the Muslim question is about the values not of Islamic, but of Western, civilization. Moving between the United States and Europe, Norton provides a fresh perspective on iconic controversies, from the Danish cartoon of Muhammad to the murder of Theo van Gogh. She examines the arguments of a wide range of thinkers--from John Rawls to Slavoj Žižek. And she describes vivid everyday examples of ordinary Muslims and non-Muslims who have accepted each other and built a common life together. Ultimately, Norton provides a new vision of a richer and more diverse democratic life in the West, one that makes room for Muslims rather than scapegoating them for the West's own anxieties.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aIslam and politics. 0aIslamxEconomic aspects. 0aIslamxSocial aspects. 0aIslamic sociology. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh  aAbu Ghraib.  aAfghanistan.  aAmerica.  aAyatollah Khomeini.  aCharlie Hebdo.  aChristianity.  aDanish cartoons.  aEurope.  aGuantnamo.  aHolocaust.  aIraq war.  aIslam.  aIslamofascism.  aJacques Derrida.  aJews.  aJohn Rawls.  aLaw of Peoples.  aMichael Muhammad Knight.  aMuselmnner.  aMuslim question.  aMuslims.  aNazism.  aPaul Berman.  aSalman Rushdie.  aSocial Justice and Islam.  aSubmission.  aTerror and Liberalism.  aThe Satanic Verses.  aThe Taqwacores.  aTheo van Gogh.  aUnited States.  aVoyous.  aWar on Terror.  aWest.  aatheism.  aclash of civilizations.  acolonization.  aconviviality.  acosmopolitanism.  aculture.  ademocracy.  aequality.  afamily.  afear.  afraternity.  afreedom of speech.  agender equality.  agraphic novels.  ahuma